description.value:
Fragmentary yellow limestone head of a male figure, the body now lost.

He wears a smooth flared wig, the ends of which are now broken off. This style likely means that the wig reached to his shoulders. His ears are slightly oversized. His eyebrows are faintly incised, and his eyes are almond shaped with traces of black paint at the outline. His nose has suffered damage with a break at the left side, but the intact right side appears slim. His lips are thick and pursed together, and are fleshy in appearance. On the reverse is a partial top section of a back-pillar. Traces of black paint and faded markings are visible across this section of the stone, but there are no clear indications of incised text.

His face has suffered two breaks at the nose and the right side cheek, with further small scratches to the wig and left side of the face. The object is now attached to a small modern base.

description.value: Terracotta reclining ithyphallic figure plaque, possibly Priapus. A reclining naked man with  receding hair and a beard, his legs extending to his right, the left bent and  close to the ground, the right with the knee raised. description.value: Terracotta figure of a devotee of Isis.  The greater part of a devotee of Isis, in full processional regalia. She wear a long chiton with a wide himation wrapped round (not an Isis-mantle, or at least not knotted at the breast; a fringe is not indicated); she also has a voluminous veil passing over her head, falling low on her left side, but less so on her right. Diagonally across her body is a tightly woven garland above a further garland consisting of bearded wheatears and three rows of round blooms; below this is a decorated textile band, one end of which hangs down in front. Her hair is arranged in a ‘melon’ style, with Isislocks falling onto her shoulders, and she wears ball earrings with an upper disc. She holds a sistrum in her raised right hand, the sistrum apparently supporting the veil. Her left arm is also bent upwards, with her left hand gripping  the veil, and a situla with a knobbed base hangs from the crook of her arm. The back is plain and has a small circular depression pierced by a vent.   Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt; minute traces of a white dressing on the front.

description.value:
Terracotta figure of male dancer.
A male grotesque, modelled in the round, dancing. He has a flattened nose, a frowning brow and is probably moustached, though facial lines may be intended. He is bald except for a line of hair extending from his temples round the back of his head. A cabled necklace or torc is worn round his neck. He leans forward from his extended bottom, his right arm akimbo, the hand on his hip, the left arm bent with his hand to his ear. His large paunch is contained in a short tunic that is stretched over his buttocks and passes over his left shoulder only, and is knotted to the right of his waist. He wears a double-wreath round his left wrist. The legs are broken off at the upper thigh, together with most of his large pendent phallus. A very small firing-vent is pierced in his back. It is possible that he had no plinth but was designed to be suspended from the hook of one of his arms.
Hollow; two-piece mould, the web cleaned up and details of the clothing… (See Merlin record for full description)
